Dear Art History & Communication Studies undergraduate students, 

We urgently request your attendance at a general assembly over zoom on Wednesday, November 20th at 5:30PM to vote on a motion supporting a student body strike on November 21st & 22nd. This collective strike, taking place across universities and CEGEPs in Montréal, is advocating for institutional divestment from McGill’s holdings in military and defense infrastructure being used to enact a genocide on Palestinians residing in Gaza and the West Bank. Unethical investments include $2.2 million in Airbus Aerospace (surveillance), $1.3 million in BAE systems (military contractor), and $500,000 in Lockheed Martin (weapons manufacturer). 

Several McGill Arts departments are also currently voting to enact this motion, including Anthropology, Philosophy, Psychology, Linguistics, and Environment. 

The AHCSSA Executive team has elected to bring this motion to a general assembly meeting open to all art history and communication studies majors and minors to form a collective decision. We are hoping to receive a vote from at least 8% of our student population, so please spread the word and encourage your peers to attend! 

Please use the link in our bio to join the meeting tomorrow. In the meantime, please email us at ahcssamcgill@gmail.com with any questions. 

Best Regards, 
AHCSSA Executive Team

The Music Library will be hosting a book launch on Friday, November 29, from 5:30pm to 7:30pm, to celebrate the publication of Between Composers: The Letters of Norma Beecroft and Harry Somers (McGill-Queen’s University Press, 2024) by Prof. Brian Cherney.

For details and to register for the event, see the link in bio 👆

In the fall of 1959 Norma Beecroft, a twenty-five-year-old composition student, left her home in Toronto and travelled to Rome to study with the eminent Italian composer Goffredo Petrassi. She left behind her lover and mentor, the thirty-four-year-old Harry Somers, by then recognized as one of Canada’s leading young composers. For the next five-and-a-half months they wrote each other almost every day. Somers soon came to realize that he wanted Beecroft to give up her studies and return to Toronto to marry him. Despite this pressure, however, she ultimately chose to remain in Italy to study and compose, thus rejecting a conventional woman’s role. Their intense and intimate correspondence documents lives lived apart but shared on the page, until the relationship ended abruptly in February 1960. As well, the letters show both composers at pivotal moments in their careers, working on their own creative projects and experiencing the music and culture in their respective environments. Beyond illuminating the evolution of their personal relationship, these wide-ranging letters not only provide much insight into the state of contemporary music in both Europe and Canada, but also evoke for the reader the general state of Canadian arts and culture in the late 1950s.

Please join us in celebrating the publication of Between Composers on November 29. Professor Cherney will speak about and read from his new book.

The Music Library will be hosting a book launch on Friday, November 22, from 5:30 to 7:30pm, to celebrate the new publication of Cadence: A Study of Closure in Tonal Music (Oxford University Press, 2024) by William Caplin, Distinguished James McGill Professor Emeritus. 

For details and to register for the event, see the link in bio 👆
 
Cadence is a comprehensive examination of how formal units in European art music of the tonal era achieve closure. Rooted in Caplin's broader “theory of formal functions,” the book develops concepts of cadence for music of the high classical style and then extends these ideas to gauge cadential practice in earlier and later style periods. Throughout the study, various manifestations of cadence are defined in terms of their harmonic-melodic morphology as well as their formal function. The book introduces a host of theoretical concepts illustrated by more than seven hundred musical examples, all of which contain extensive analytical annotations of harmony, melody, cadence, and form. 
 
Please join us in celebrating the publication of Cadence: A Study of Closure in Tonal Music. Professor Caplin will speak about his new book and copies will be available for purchase at a discount.

In a world where students rely more and more on digital technology and AI for learning, English majors Avryl Bender and Jayda Smith were tasked with “researching the ungoogleable” during their summer internship with Poetry Matters. 

During their internship, Avryl and Jayda conducted research on Dr. Barbara Althea Jones—a Trinidadian-born poet, plant geneticist, and professor at McGill during the sixties. 

“In the archive, time moved differently. Gradually, the past and present seemed to fold into each other. Both of us remember particular moments when the archive prompted us to feel that we really knew Jones,” Avryl and Jayda share their experience working in the Barbara Althea Jones fonds within the McGill University Archives. 

Keep an eye out on the Poetry Matters website (https://www.mcgill.ca/poetrymatters/) for Avryl and Jayda’s forthcoming portrait of Dr. Barbara Althea Jones and make sure to read the full article via the link in our bio.

In our last Faculty Publication Spotlight we spoke to Camille Owens, assistant professor of English, about her latest book, “Like Children: Black Prodigy and the Measure of the Human in America”, published by New York University Press in October 2024. 

It was during her time as a graduate student at Yale University that Owens came across a photograph of Oscar Moore, who would grace the cover of her first book years later. 

Oscar Moore, a black, blind child who performed across American stages as a prodigy during the 1880s-1890s, prompted Owens to look into the status and treatment of black children in both its historical and contemporary context. 

“Upon finding [this picture of Moore], I immediately wanted to know who Moore was, and why, in a period where white supremacists were relentlessly questioning black intelligence, this child’s intelligence—or “brightness”—held entertainment value for white Americans,” says Owens.

This Friday’s talk: Karlos Arregi (University of Chicago): The relation between head movement and periphrasis.

“In joint work with Asia Pietraszko, I’ve been investigating the relation between head movement and the synthesis-periphrasis distinction in the verbal domain. We use the term “synthesis” to refer to verbal expressions in which the lexical verb bears all the verbal inflection in a clause (e.g. “rode” in English). In contrast, a periphrastic verbal expression additionally contains an auxiliary verb (specifically, “be” or “have”), and verbal inflection is distributed between the lexical verb and the auxiliary (e.g. “had ridden”). We argue for two crosslinguistic generalizations: AfTonomy and *V-Aux. According to AfTonomy, affixal Ts vary as to whether they are in a head movement relation with a verb. *V-Aux states that in periphrasis, the lexical verb and the auxiliary cannot be related by head movement. Existing analyses of periphrasis can account for one or the other generalization, but not for both. We further argue that this tension between the two generalizations is resolved if we adopt the hypothesis that both head movement and periphrasis are tied to selection. More specifically, we propose that head movement is parasitic on a selectional relation (following Svenonius 1994, Julien 2002, Matushansky 2006, and Preminger 2019) and that auxiliaries are merged as specifiers selected by functional heads such as T (Pietraszko 2017).”

The library is a valuable resource for the broader McGill community and visiting scholars and welcomes all members of the public. 💛
